      <h1 class="font-heading text-3xl sm:text-4xl md:text-5xl leading-tight">Best Hardwood Floor Colors for Houston Homes</h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-brand-ink/70 text-sm">Published May 2026 · By Joey Jamail</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <article class="container mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 pb-16 max-w-3xl text-brand-ink/90 leading-relaxed text-[1.0625rem]">

    <p>Houston light is bright, warm, and unique. Floors that look beautiful in a New York apartment can look orange in a Memorial living room with south-facing windows. We get this question constantly — what color of hardwood actually works in Houston homes?</p>

    <p class="mt-4">The honest answer: <strong>neutral medium tones work everywhere. Light tones work in north-facing or open-plan rooms. Dark tones are riskier and trend out faster.</strong> Below, the long version with specifics.</p>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">What makes Houston light different</h2>
    <p>Three things to know about light in Houston homes:</p>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
      <li><strong>Warm afternoon light.</strong> Houston's late-day sun is warm, yellow-orange. Floors with warm undertones can read overly orange in this light.</li>
      <li><strong>High intensity year-round.</strong> Our windows let in more total light than northern markets. Floors fade and shift faster.</li>
      <li><strong>Big windows.</strong> Houston homes — especially new builds and Memorial / River Oaks — have larger window-to-wall ratios than national averages. The floor catches a lot of direct light.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">The four color categories</h2>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-xl text-brand-coal mt-8 mb-3">1. Light floors (blonde, pale honey, white-washed)</h3>
    <p><strong>Works for:</strong> Modern interiors, small rooms that need to feel larger, north-facing rooms that need more apparent light, families who want a clean Scandinavian feel.</p>
    <p class="mt-3"><strong>Caution:</strong> Pale floors show pet hair and dust more. They also age into yellowness if they're poor quality — premium European oak ambers gracefully, but cheap engineered floors can turn unpleasant orange-yellow.</p>
    <p class="mt-3"><strong>Houston-specific note:</strong> In south-facing rooms, light floors can look slightly orange in afternoon light. Choose floors with cool undertones (like Harbor Cloud) rather than warm to neutralize this.</p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-xl text-brand-coal mt-8 mb-3">2. Warm floors (honey, caramel, amber)</h3>
    <p><strong>Works for:</strong> Traditional and transitional homes, rooms with cool-toned cabinetry or marble, homes wanting warmth and character. Pairs beautifully with brass hardware.</p>
    <p class="mt-3"><strong>Caution:</strong> In Houston's warm afternoon light, very warm floors can over-amplify the warm tones in the room. Balance with cooler wall colors.</p>
    <p class="mt-3"><strong>Houston pick:</strong> Amber Canyon. Hand-oiled European white oak with honey undertones. Reads warm but not orange.</p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-xl text-brand-coal mt-8 mb-3">3. Neutral floors (mid-tone, taupe, soft brown)</h3>
    <p><strong>Works for:</strong> Almost everything. Goes with white walls, gray walls, warm walls, cool walls. Pairs with any cabinetry, any countertop, any sofa.</p>
    <p class="mt-3"><strong>The forever choice.</strong> If you're going to live in the home long-term and don't want to commit to a strong design aesthetic, neutral wins. It's also the safest resale choice.</p>
    <p class="mt-3"><strong>Houston pick:</strong> Sierra Driftwood. Soft taupe-gray with brown undertones. Most-installed floor across our Houston projects.</p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-xl text-brand-coal mt-8 mb-3">4. Dark floors (espresso, walnut, chocolate)</h3>
    <p><strong>Works for:</strong> Formal traditional homes, libraries, smaller statement rooms. Dark floors can look stunning.</p>
    <p class="mt-3"><strong>Caution — heavy:</strong> Dark floors show dust, hair, footprints, and crumbs more than any other color. In Houston's bright light, dark floors also fade unevenly under direct sun within a few years.</p>
    <p class="mt-3"><strong>Trend warning:</strong> Espresso-dark floors peaked around 2010. They read as dated in many 2026 contexts. If you choose dark, choose carefully and commit.</p>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">What designers specify most in Houston</h2>
    <p>Across the Houston design firms we work with, the rough breakdown of color specifications in 2026:</p>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
      <li><strong>Neutral mid-tone:</strong> ~50% of specifications</li>
      <li><strong>Warm honey:</strong> ~25% of specifications</li>
      <li><strong>Light/blonde:</strong> ~20% of specifications</li>
      <li><strong>Dark/espresso:</strong> ~5% of specifications</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-3">The dark-floor trend that dominated 2008–2015 is firmly over. Neutral and warm dominate now.</p>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">How to actually choose</h2>
    <p>The single best advice: <strong>get samples and lay them on your actual floor in your actual light for a week.</strong> Photos and showroom lighting lie. Houston light is unique. The same floor that looked perfect in the store might look orange or gray in your home.</p>
    <p class="mt-3">Our sample box lets you order up to 6 full-size planks free, shipped to your Houston address in 5–7 days. Lay them in your living room. See how they look at 9am, noon, and 5pm. The decision usually makes itself.</p>

